            <h2>Quotes</h2>
            <blockquote>"Be the change that you wish to see in the world."</blockquote>
            <cite>- Mahatma Gandhi</cite>
            <blockquote>"The best way to find yourself is to lose yourself in the service of others."</blockquote>
            <cite>- Mahatma Gandhi</cite>
            <blockquote>"An eye for an eye only ends up making the whole world blind."</blockquote>
            <cite>- Mahatma Gandhi</cite>
            <blockquote>"Live as if you were to die tomorrow. Learn as if you were to live forever."</blockquote>
            <cite>- Mahatma Gandhi</cite>
        </section>
        <section class="legacy">
            <h2>Legacy</h2>
            <p>Mahatma Gandhi's impact extends far beyond the borders of India. His philosophy of nonviolence influenced global leaders and movements, including the American civil rights movement led by Martin Luther King Jr., Nelson Mandela's struggle against apartheid in South Africa, and numerous other efforts for social justice and human rights around the world.</p>
            <p>Gandhi's teachings on simplicity, self-reliance, and sustainability are increasingly relevant in today's world. His emphasis on ethical living and his vision for a just and equitable society continue to inspire new generations to work towards peace and justice.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="personal-reflections">
            <h2>Personal Reflections</h2>
            <p>Mahatma Gandhi's unwavering commitment to nonviolence and his ability to mobilize millions for the cause of freedom and justice continue to inspire me. His teachings on simplicity, self-reliance, and communal harmony resonate deeply with me and many others. Gandhi's legacy reminds us of the power of peaceful resistance and the importance of standing up for what is right.</p>
            <p>In my own life, I strive to embody the principles that Gandhi lived by. His message of love, tolerance, and nonviolence is a guiding light in times of conflict and uncertainty. Gandhi's life is a testament to the idea that one person can indeed make a difference, and his legacy serves as a reminder of the enduring power of truth and nonviolence.</p>
        </section>
